<section class="container page">
  <h1 class="page__title">Join us</h1>
  <p class="page__lede">The best way to understand our group is to look around the site. If what you see resonates, we would like to hear from you. We are hiring at all levels, and we value your character — curiosity, creativity, honesty, generosity and a collaborative spirit — as much as your past experience. Below are the routes in; if none fits exactly but the work excites you, reach out anyway.</p>

  <div class="join-grid">
    <article class="join-card">
      <h2>PhD students</h2>
      <p>There are two routes into a PhD with us. Each year the Department of Aeronautics runs a competitive round of fully funded PhD Studentships (covering fees and a tax-free stipend), with applications typically opening in the autumn and closing in early January. Outside that round, you can also apply at any time by first contacting a supervisor to develop a project, then submitting a formal application through Imperial's online system — naming your proposed supervisor and any funding you are seeking.</p>
      <p>Either way, email me first with your CV and a short note on why AIM Lab: <a href="mailto:{{ site.email }}">{{ site.email }}</a>.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="join-card">
      <h2>Postdocs</h2>
      <p>Funded postdoc positions are advertised here and on Imperial's jobs site when available. I also welcome candidates who want to apply for a fellowship together — Imperial Research Fellowships, Royal Society, Marie Skłodowska-Curie, Royal Academy of Engineering, and similar. These are competitive and have early deadlines, so get in touch well ahead of time to discuss fit and develop a proposal.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="join-card">
      <h2>Undergraduate &amp; MEng</h2>
      <p>Imperial undergraduates can join through UROP (the Undergraduate Research Opportunities Programme) — a supervised research experience, usually 6–10 weeks over the summer, sometimes part-time in term. A UROP can also grow into a final-year project. Most placements are arranged directly with the supervisor rather than advertised, so email with your year, course, and a sentence on what draws you to our work.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="join-card">
      <h2>Visitors</h2>
      <p>Visiting students and researchers with their own funding are welcome for short or extended stays. Email at least three months ahead of your intended dates with a short description of what you would like to work on.</p>
    </article>
  </div>
</section>
